<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-106-404 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 001 622</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 15 1991 v8 n28 p15(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Signetics takes the wraps off industry's first digital encoder.andO;(Signetics SAA7199 chip) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Damore, Kelley.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Signetics Co. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   Signetics SAA7199 (Integrated circuit) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     EncodersComputer graphicsProduct IntroductionIntegrated circuitsDigital CommunicationsSemiconductor industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Kelley DamoreandM;Signetics Co. last week introduced a digital encoder that allows users tooutput computer graphics and digital video to such sources as television,high-resolution displays and videotape.andM;To date, board makers have had to incorporate analog encoders from companiessuch as Motorola Inc., into video frame-grabber boards.andM;Signetics' SAA7199 chip, however, is the first digital solution on themarket, said officials at Signetics in Sunnyvale, Calif.andM;&quot;A digital encoder gives users a crisper signal andlsqb;than analogandrsqb;, resulting in aclean picture,&quot; said Michael Maietta, vice president of engineering for boardmaker RasterOps Corp., which is evaluating the chip for future products.andM;&quot;It will enhance output quality without too much cost,&quot; Maietta said.andP;  Aboard incorporating the chip would cost only about $20 more than boards usingMotorola's encoder, he added.andM;Other candidates for boards using the new SAA7199 encoder include HauppaugeComputer Works Inc., New Media Graphics Corp., Chips and Technologies Inc.,andO;Sun Microsystems Inc., NeXT Computer Inc. and IBM.andM;Boards incorporating the new chip could debut as early as Siggraph, scheduledfor later this month, officials said.andM;The chip, available now in sample quantities, is priced at $47 in quantitiesof 100, officials said.andP;  Volume production is expected to begin in the fourthquarter.andM;Signetics is a subsidiary of North American Phillips Corp.andO;</TEXT></DOC>